{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503332"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2015"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2015"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.67,0.18,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54858"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2015"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40391"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"3945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54858"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the emergency department complaining of sudden onset vertigo, accompanied by dysphagia, diplopia and nystagmus. On examination, there is noticeable LEFT sided facial ptosis, miosis and altered facial sensation over trigeminal distribution. There is also marked ataxia in her LEFT upper and lower limbs. On her RIGHT side there is also loss of pain and sensation of her trunk and limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Lateral medullary syndrome","Brainstem stroke","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome","Vertebrobasilar insufficiency"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUpper and lower limb power is dependent on the corticospinal (ie motor) pathway, which travels medially through the brainstem. The remaining signs are all seen with conditions affecting the \u003Cstrong\u003Espinothalamic and spinocerebellar\u003C/strong\u003E, as well as the sympathetic pathway and sensory nucleus of CN V, which all run laterally (or down the side) through the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe spinothalamic tract, conveying pain and temperature sensation, and the spinocerebellar tracts, crucial for proprioception and coordination, both run laterally within the medulla. Consequently, deficits in these pathways can lead to symptoms like\u003Cstrong\u003E contralateral sensory disturbances and ipsilateral ataxia, hallmark features of LMS\u003C/strong\u003E. Additionally, the sympathetic pathway responsible for \u003Cstrong\u003EHorner\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E and the \u003Cstrong\u003Esensory nucleus of the trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN V) contributing to facial sensation are situated laterally within the medulla.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVertigo, \u003Cstrong\u003Edizziness\u003C/strong\u003E, nausea and vomiting, and symptoms like skew deviation, diplopia, and severe gait ataxia could be due to the pathology of the vestibular nuclei or vestibular\u2013cerebellar connections. \u003Cstrong\u003EDysphagia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as a result of the inclusion of swallowing centres situated in the dorsolateral region of the medulla oblongata, involving the nucleus ambiguous, nucleus tractus solitarius, and the reticular formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple Sclerosis (MS)\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a variety of neurological symptoms, including sensory disturbances, weakness, and coordination problems, the sudden onset of symptoms described in the scenario, along with the specific combination of findings such as Horner syndrome, ipsilateral loss of pain and temperature sensation in the face, and ataxia, is not typical for MS. \u003Cstrong\u003EBrainstem strokes \u003C/strong\u003Eoften present with a combination of symptoms affecting multiple cranial nerves rather than characteristic findings seen in lateral medullary syndrome. \u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (GBS) typically presents with symmetrical ascending weakness, starting in the legs and often progressing to involve the arms and respiratory muscles, whereas the symptoms described in the scenario suggest a more localized neurological lesion affecting structures in the lateral medulla. While \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebrobasilar insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can cause symptoms such as dizziness, vertigo, and dysphagia, it typically does not produce the specific findings of lateral medullary syndrome, such as Horner syndrome and contralateral sensory deficits. Moreover, the marked ataxia in the right upper and lower limbs and problems coordinating movements seen in this case are not typical features of vertebrobasilar insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Understanding the neuroanatomical pathways involved in lateral medullary syndrome aids in recognizing the expected ipsilateral manifestations."],"references":["Ibrahim AA, Bakir A, Sidow NO, Ali AM, Osman MF, Ahmed A, Hassan MS. Lateral medullary syndrome: uncommon form of brainstem stroke. Annals of Medicine and Surgery. 2023 Mar;85(3):542.","Cadogan, L. H. a. M. (2021, July 22). Wallenberg Syndrome. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. https://litfl.com/wallenberg-syndrome/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40391"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2015"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40391"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-11T10:31:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-12T21:46:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2015"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54858"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},